{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958050201/0256.xml":{"full_text":"Inquiring\nReporter\n66\nIF hat advice would you give to people who\nare about to retire so they can better enjoy their\nyears of leisure?\u201d\nAsked of members of the Region 2-B, UAW, Pen*\nsioners Club.)\nPelton\nBrinkeroff\nWilliam Felton, 2095 Kenison\n\u201cThe advice I would give is for\nthose retiring to enjoy life by\ngoing to a number of clubs that\ninterest him and to be pleasant\nto everyone. In this way it will\nbenefit his health and he will\nenjoy life much more.'1\nEarl Brinkeroff, 1034 Colburn;\n\u201cThe only thing I can say is for\npeople to retire as soon as pos- i\nsible for health's sake. I also\nwould advice him to have some-1\nthing to do to keep his mind offj\nhis troubles. Keep busy and you'\nwill be happy.\u201d\n\nWe\u201d\nwrabbiyothn\nErd\nBinder\nAnna Erd, 1020 Moore: \"I feel\na person should retire and enjoy\nlife while you can and not work\ntill you die. It's later than you\nthink so keep your mind active\nwith current affairs and you\nwon't be bored. I have done this\nand it has kept me happy.\"\nMayme Binder, 6301 Bush\n\"My advice is to retire and stay\nretired. By this I mean not to\ntake any other part time job or\nfull time job which will take\nwork away from the younger\npeople. We should also get ac\ntive in politics to get more Social\nSecurity and other gains that the\nunion is trying to get for the\nworker.\"\nL\nA\nLogan\nHubbard\nGeorge Logan, 3263 Black-1\natone \"Everyone should retire;\nwhen they can get their benefits\nbecause nowadays you can stay\nactive by going to union affairs.\nBy keeping healthy you can be\nhappy because health is the most\nimportant gift a man has.\u201d\nCAPITAL TIRE A RUBBER CO.\nAt Low Price*\nCHerry s-2311\nNationally Famous\n1001 Cherry Street\nA Good Service for Auto Workers\u2014\n(WAVAy) TOLEDO AUTO CLUB\n2271 Ashland Avenue\nCII. 1-4142\nUNION\nI\nTrading Post\nRates: 10 cenh a line (5 word\u00bb), minimum 2 lince, (Ml\nctnli. Mail with rath or bring in to Room 2(13, 245 V in\nthrop Street, CH. 1-9126, txlemion 33.\nFuneral Directors\nDAY-EDWARDS MORTUARY\nCH 4-0751\n741\nW.\nCentral\nAve\nHOEFLINGER MORTUARY\n901 PUtt St\n0X^1-8768\nFOTH MORTUARY\n3310 Jefferson Ave\nCH 1-3241\nABELE FUNERAL HOME\n1*10 Cherry St\nCH 3 0101\nPARKS D EMMERT FUNERAL HOME\n3883 Monroe St.\nGR 2-21 in\nH. H. BIRKENKAMP FUNERAL\nHOMES\u20141003 Broadwav\nTRILBY. Ohio, GR 4-3773\nCH 3-2183\nBROWN FUNERAL HOME\nBl* Grand Ave.\nCH 3-8433\nTelevision Sets\nTV SET Home appliances all types.\n1854 W. Central Ave\nHardware Supplies\nPAINTS all kind*. low prices. Colon\nUl Hardware 1854 Central\nUsed Cars\nFOR SALE: Jeep Station Wagons\n4-wheel drive. Call CH 2-0071.\nGlenn Hubbard, Temperance,\nMich.: \"If a person doesn't have\nany hobbies or anything to do\nhe should keep working. I keep\nbusy by working in the garden\nand doing repairs at home. I\nwork just as hard as I did before\nand am happy doing this.\u201d\nFlorence Cox, 2473 Maple\nwood: \"I would rather be work\ning because I miss my friends at\nwork but I try to keep active by\ngoing to different affairs, read\ning and doing anything else that\nI like to do.\u201d\nCox\nClyde Cox, 2473 Maplewood:\n\u201cDo anything your health will\npermit such as dancing, hunting,\nfishing and enjoy yourself with\nthe crowd. In this way you will\ntake everything off your mind\nthat might disturb you. You can t\nbe bored if you are active.\"\nOhio Merger\n(Continued from Page 1)\nmerger agreement were worked\nout by the executive boards of\nthe merging bodies, and approv\ned January 28.\nThree Officers\nThey call for three full-time\npaid officials a president and\nexecutive vice president, both to\nbe elected from AFL affiliates,\na\nand a secretary-treasurer,\ncome from the CIO unions.\nto\nAlso due to be elected are 24\nvice presidents, 10 to be elected\nfrom the AFL and 14 from the\nCIO\nThe vice presidents and\nthe three top officers will con-\nstitute the executive board.\nThe new merged House of\nLabor will be preparing itself\nfor battle against one of the most\ndetermined efforts to destroy the\neffectiveness of unions which\nhas ever been waged in Ohio\u2014\nthe effort by anti-labor forces to\nmake the open shop compulsory.\nPledges of support in this\nfight will be made by many\ndelegations at the convention.\nOther issues with which the\ndelegates will be concerned in\nclude the Supplemental Unem\nployment Benefits, now blocked\nin Ohio, and the forthcoming\nNovember elections.\nHOLMES\nWindow Cleaning Service\nFREE ESTIMATES\n1118 W. Bancroft CH. 6-7965\nService\nUNCLE JOHN'S Food Co., catering toj\nparties and banquet* RA. 6-1110.\nI\nGERBER CABINET SHOP\u2014Spectalist\nin kitchen remodeling. CH 3-9337 i\nPAY water, gas phone. light bill* at\nLocal 12 due* window\nMail your Sale* Tax Stamp* to F\nI\nReno. 425 Winthrop St\nNEW YORK Life Insurance Co Rich\nard C. Duftey Agent CH 8-6481\nHall For Rent\u2014Kitchen factlitien, 3015\nDetroit near Central CH 6-4806.\nCOTTON SHAG RUGS washed dried.:\ndyed re-rubberized 3-Hour service\u2019\non most rug* Friendly Laundrymat.\n3644 Upton Ave GR 4-6086\nFURNACES A Envestrough installed\nReasonable. Call RA. #-0633.\nThe Tip-Top Room First Main St.\navailable for Receptions Parties. Meet\ning*. Call CH 3-3700\u2014 EL. 1739\nMitcellaneoug\nEclectic\nFOR SALE McGutfeys\nSpeyer Call Grand Rapid* 31137\n14' Freelander Boat\u2014Retort Model\n$63. CH. 3-4768\ntt tlurt tomething you no longer need and would like\nto give away to help tome other union member? Jutt call\nour \"Give Away Column,\u201d CHerry 1-9126, Lxt. 33.\n1\nJ\n\nRecession\nIs Worse\nThan Four\nComparative studies indicate\nthat the current recession is\nmore serious than four milder\nrecessions since 1920, including\n[those in 1948-49 and 1953-54,\n'Geoffrey Moore, associate direc\ntor of research of the National\nBureau of Economic Research,\ntold AFL-CIO research directors\nat a meeting in Washington.\nHowever, he added, it is less\nsevere than the more serious\nones of 1920-1, 1929-33 and\n1937-8.\nMoore spoke at a luncheon\nwhich closed a two-day meeting\nduring which research directors\nof national and international un\nions and their staffs met with\nAFL-CIO economists for a dis\ncussion of mutual problems and\nan examination of the recession\nand where it is leading. Most of\nthe discussions were technical in\nnature.\nIt opened with a review of the\nbargaining situation in the light\nof the economy with Seymour\nBrandwein, AFL-CIO economist,\nin the chair. Research Dir.\nWoodrow Ginsberg of the Auto\nWorkers discussed that union's\nnegotiations and Otto Pragen,\nresearch director of the Chemi\ncal Workers, talked on major\nnon-wage items.\nA general review of the eco\nnomic situation was given by\nNat Goldfinger, AFL-CIO\neco\nnomist, at a session devoted to\nthe next steps in combatting the\nrecession. Research Dir. Charles\nDonahue of the Plumbers and\nSteamfitters gave the point of\nview in the building trades. The\nsituation in \"hard goods\u201d\nwas\ndiscussed by Research Dir. Otis\nBrubaker of the Steelworkers.\nAt another meeting Murray\nWernick, labor economist with\nthe Federal Reserve Board, told\nof recent developments in pro\nductivity and its statistics. Com\nment was given by Research Dir.\nEverett Kassalow of the AFL\nCIO Industrial Union Dept. and\nResearch Dir. David Lasser of\nthe Electrical, Radio Machine\nWorkers. i\nNew Director Set\nFor Choral Society\nReorganization of the Toledo\nChoral Society, with a new di\nrector and a new tally of offi\ncers, has been completed and\nthe society is announcing its\nimmediate plans.\nSamuel F. Szor has been\nen\ngaged as conductor. Mr. Szor is\na graduate of the University of\nMichigan at Ann Arbor with a\nBA and MA in Music. He is in\nstructor of instrumental music at\nToledo Woodward High School,\nChoir Director at the Broadway\nMethodist Church, Bassoonist for\nthe Toledo Orchestra and Direc\ntor of Music Under The Stars\nBand Concert Series in Wal\nbridge Park.\nMary Clark Anderson, Minis\nter of Music at Monroe Street\nMethodist Church will be the\nac\ncompanist.\nThe new officers are: Donald\nE. Good, President; Paul DeWitt,\nVice President; Mildred Connin,\nRecording Secretary; Ellen Mal\nlory, Corresponding Secretary;\nMargaret Spencer, Treasurer.\nThe society is planning two\nsummer concerts in addition to\na performance of Haydn's \u201cCrea\ntion\" on the Lakeside Associa\ntion Summer Program, Lakeside,\nOhio. The two summer concerts\nare tentatively planned as out\ndoor programs in the Zoo Am\nphitheater.\nThe dues for this summer sea\nson will be $3.\nIt Was Toledo U. Day at Solidarity House\nUniversity of Toledo class in Business Ad*\nministration heard another side of the\nmanagement-labor story when it traveled\nto UAW's Solidarity House last week to\nhear talks hy Roy Reuther, the union\u2019s\npolitical action director, and George\nWeaver of the Research and Engineering\nDept. Here, Roy Reuther tells the 16 stu\nAuto Companies Reject\nUAW \u2018Sell Cars\u2019 Plan\n(Continued from Page 1)\nVice President Woodcock\npointed out that the GM reply\n\u201ccompletely ignores the tre\nmendous economic burden\u201d\nwhich the big new car inven\ntory places on the industry it\nself and the entire economy.\nThe big company\u2019s response\nalso ignores the UAW's willing\nness to join in measures which\nwould move the big inventory,\nand provide sorely needed relief\nto the more than 100,000 GM\nworkers laid off through no fault\nof their own, the GM director\ndeclared\n\u201cUnwilling to Help\u201d\nin commenting an Ford's re\njection, Ken Bannon. director of\nthe union's National Ford Dept.,\ncharged that the Ford company\nwas \u201cunwilling to help solve\neconomic problems which are in\nlarge part of its own making.\u201d\nMr. Bannon said:\n\"The sag in auto production\nand sales, which has led to rec\nord inventories of new cars.\nthrown hundreds of thousands of\npeople out of work and helped\ndepress the whole American\neconomy, is in part attributable\nto Fords unjustifiable pricing\npolicies over the postwar years.\n\"There is absolutely nothing\nin Ford\u2019s latest proposal which\nwould help in any way to end\n75,000 Votes Are Expected\n(Continued from Pace 1)\nfire on a claim that their school\ndistricts will be consolidated\nwith that of Toledo. These con\ntentions have been refuted by\nthe Toledo Board of Education\nand the State Board of Educa\ntion.\nThey\nhave\nmade\nit\nclear\nthat there is no intention to eli\nminate the two township school\ndistricts.\nFurther, Council at its meet\ning Monday served notice that\nif the two townships annex, it\nwill allocate a portion of its pay\nroll income tax from the Toledo\nschools to the two township\nschool districts.\nRaces For Office\nSelections in the parly pri\nmaries will include the offices\nof governor, U. S. senator, lieu\ntenant governor, secretary of\nstate, state treasurer, attorney\ngeneral, judges of the Ohio Su\npreme Court and Court of Ap\npeals, representative to Con\ngress, members of the Ohio\nMouse and Senate and various\nCounty officials, notably County\n\"Don't just stand there see if the gas hose reaches my tank\" j\nHerb\u2019s Gulf Service\nCOLLINGWOOD at ASHLAND\nCH. 1.0432\nDETROIT at PHILLIPS\nClem\u2019s Marathon Service\nGR. 2-0342\nMiller\u2019s Pure Oil Service\nBERDAN at HAVERHILL\nGR. 5-7581\ni\nTony\u2019s Gulf Service\nDETROIT at LAWRENCE CH. 14)069\n\u2014Photo by Jim Yardley, UAW\ndents \u201cWhy unions are in politics.\u201d Prof.\nLouis Hough of TU is partially obscured\nby Roy Reuther\u2019s gesturing hands. The\nextra-curricular class was arranged by\nHarold Mouch, Region 2-B education di\nrector, as part of a continuing effort to in\nform students of the work and objectives\nof unions.\nSUB Costs GM\nNext to Nothing\nit\u2019s costing General Motors\npractically nothing to pay out\nSUB benefits to its 100,000\nlaid-off workers.\nThe UAW disclosed that just\nthe interest on the $98 milljon\nin GM's SUB trust fund paid\nfor nearly two-thirds of the\n$7,056,000 in benefits to laid\noff workers through March of\n1958,\nThat left $95,145,000 in the\ntrust fund as of April 4, de\nspite the benefits paid out and\nthe great number of workers\nlaid off.\n\u201cThis simple arithmetic,\u201d\nsaid the UAW in a letter to\nGM, prompted the union to\npropose that GM extend SUB\nbenefits for its laid-off work\ners.\nThe proposal, which would\nhave helped thousands of\nworkers and their families,\nwould not have cost GM one\ncent. But GM rejected the en\ntire proposal.\n\u2022~PRRRR5RVP555R55P55V555PV9RVV555V5555P55R55R55-5PVccr\u00ab\nthe present downturn or to bring\nabout an increase in auto sales\nand production.\u201d\nI Commissioner.\nIn the Republican primary,\nGov. C. William O\u2019Neill has only\ntoken opposition for his post\nfrom Charles P. Taft of Cincin\nnati. But in the Democratic pri\nmary, seven candidates will con\ntest the nomination for governor.\nChief interest in the Lucas\nCounty Democratic primary\ncenters in the races, aside that\nof governor, for representa\ntive to Congress, county com\nmissioner and representative\nto the Ohio General Assembly.\nAshley Challenged\nin the race for the seat from\nI the Ninth Ohio Congressional\nDistrict, Congressman Thomas\n(Lud) Ashley is being challeng\ned by Frailer Reams, who pre\nviously was elected as an Inde\npendent, unseating Congressman\nTom Burke.\nSix Democrats are seeking the\npost of County Commissioner.\nExpected to offer the greatest\nchallenge to the present incum\nbent, Ray Gedert, is former Vice\nMayor Ned Skeldon, who served\ntwo terms in City Council.\nFourteen candidates are seek\ning the five spots for Ohio Rep\nresentative in the Democratic\nprimary. Seeking re-election to\nhis third term is State Rep.\nFrancis, F. Reno of Local 12.\nAmong other labor candidates\nwho are making the race are\nThomas P. Curley, vice president\nof Local 9, Glassworkers and a\nformer member of the Spicer\nUnit and Ernest Jurski of\nSpicer.\n1 Following its usual custom,\nthe United Labor Committee has\nrefrained from making any en\ndorsements in the primary.\nl\nGas Union Sets\nMeeting May 13\nThe next regular union meet\nl ing of Local 349 Utility Workers\nUnion of America will be held\nat 134 Summit St. at 8 p.m. on\nTuesday, May 13. The Execu\ntive- Board will meet promptly\nat 7:30 p.m.\nThis will be an important\ni meeting, as officers for the com\ning year will be nominated, R. L.\nButler, president, announced.\nRails Warned\nThey May Be\nRun by U. S.\nA warning that the federal\ngovernment may have to run the\ncountry's railroads was sounded\nby Chairman G. E. Leighty of\nthe Railway Labor Executives\u2019,\nAssociation as he concluded les-'\ntimony before the Senate sub\ncommittee conducting hearings\non the \u201cprecarious\u201d plight of the\ncarriers.\n\u201cIf the railroads are going\nto be operated to the benefit\nof corporate financiers as some\nare at present,\u201d he said, \u201ccon\nsideration must be given to\ngovernment ownership and op\neration in order to protect the\npublic.\u201d\nEarlier Leighty, president of\nthe Railway Telegraphers, and\nother rail labor spokesmen had\naccused the railroads of \u201cwhin-,\ning\u201d instead of fighting for busi\nness, and of trying to kill pas-1\nsenger and some other services\nin favor of the more profitable\ncarload lot freight.\nDeny Featherbedding\nThe labor witnesses also re-.\nI\nbutted charges of \u201cfeatherbed\nding\u201d raised by the railroads\nduring their testimony and\npressed by Sen. Frank Lausche\n(D-Ohio), a member of the sub\ncommittee.\nPres. H. E. Gilbert of the Lo\ncomotive Firemen Enginemen,\nin reply to a question, told\nLausche that the rule that 100\nmiles of travel earns an operat\ning employe a day's pay was in\nstituted by the railroads them-'\nselves in the 1880s. Not until\n1956 did they ask for a change,\nhe said, and then voluntarily\nwithdrew the request. At any\nrate, he added, the rule applies\nonly to about 25 percent of all\nrailroad workers.\nWe can do anything we want\nto do if we stick to it long\nenough.\n\u2014Helen Keller\nSee Us Also For:\nBoat, Trailer, Window,\nFurniture Desk Top Glass\nWalt\u2019s\nAuto\nGlass\nSuperior at Washington\nCH. 3-8136\nGIVE\nYOURSELF\nA GOOD\nBRAKE\nBy The\nExperts\nTURNER\nBRAKE SERVICE\n111-14th St. CH. 3*8255\nAL EDWARDS'\nWheel Alignment\nFront End Rebuilding\nWheel Balancing and\nBrake Service\n2136 MONROE\nCH 1-3345\nI\nUNDERCOATING\nALL\nCARS\nComplete Undercoating, including Hood,\nFenders. Gas Tank and Underbody\nWe use the finest undercoating material\navailable. Guaranteed. Steam cleaning\n*17\nTOLEDO UNDERCOATING CO.\nOpen 8-6 Monday Through Saturday\n4345 Monroe St. (Near Secor Rd.) New Exchange GB. 5-1811\nV\n\nL\nJobless, Living Costs\nBoth at Record Peak\nLiving costs soared to a\nnew record high in mid\nMarch as millions of unem\nployed workers were trying,\nto get by on inadequate job-,\nless benefits. savings or wel\nfare assistance. I\nThe Labor Dept. reported that'\nits living cost index climbed'\nseven-tenths of one percent from\nmid-February to mid-March 1\nwith higher food prices account\ning for about 80 percent of the\nincrease.\nLabor Statistics Commissioner*\nEwan Clague declined to predict!\nany drop in living costs for:\nApril indicating that the index is,\nnot expected to move very much\neither up or down.\nThe latest increase will\nbring pay increases of from 2\nto 4 cents an hour for over\none million railroi\n1, electri\ncal, metal, chemical and trans\nportation workers.\nThe Auto Workers executive,\nboard warned that living-cost I\njumps spelled\ndeep personal\ntragedy\u201d to millions of unem-:\nployed, short-week workers and\npeople on pensions and relief.\n\u201cAggressive and prompt federal\naction\u201d on jobless compensation,\npublic works and a tax cut offer'\nthe \u201conly serious hope,\u201d the\nUAW said.\nAnnouncement of the new liv\ning cost increase came almost\nsimultaneously with Pres. Eisen\nhower's news conference at\nwhich he declared that the reces\nsion has been flattening out for\nsome time and warned Ameri\ncans against becoming hysterical\nabout the slump.\nIke Opposes Tax Cut\nHe repeated his opposition to\na tax cut and made it clear that\nthere is no imminent request to\nCongress for a reduction.\nEisenhower\u2019s statement\ncame a few days after the Fed\neral Reserve Board, on record\nas worried about the impact of\na future inflation, cut the dis\nToledo Veterans Losing\nUnemployment Insurance\nSolidarity Post 63 of the\nAMVETS in Toledo, made up\nmostly of union workers, is\nseeking to correct a Bureau\nof Unemployment Compensa\ntion rule which is depriving\nmany veterans of their unem\nployment insurance.\nA resolution pointing out the\ninjustice, and calling for im\nmediate correction, has been\ndrawn up by the Post for pre\nsentation to the Ohio State Con\nvention of the AMVETS in June.\nCopies have been sent to the\nNinth District Council of the\norganization and to the adjutant\nof the Department of Ohio with\na request for immediate action\nto enable the veterans to begin\ndrawing compensation at once.\nJohn D. Smith and Edward\nBodi of the Post, who signed the\nresolution, cite the example of\na young Toledo worker who re\ncently got out of the service.\nHe returned to his former\njob in a Toledo plant, but af\nter working a little over a\nmonth, was laid off. When he\napplied. for compensation, he\nwas denied it because he did\nnot have the necessary 20\nweeks of employment \u201cwith-*\nin his base year.\u201d\n1\nWhile it was true he did not\nhave 20 weeks of employment\nafter returning from service, he\nhad worked for this employer\nfor over two years before going\ninto service. He would have been\neligible for compensation, in\nother words, if he had not gone\ninto military service.\nI\nUnder the Federal govern\nment\u2019s provision for veterans,:\nthose who enter military service\nafter Jan. 31, 1955 are not eli\ngible for compensation.\nThe BUC requires a worker\nto have 20 weeks of work dur-;\ning the year preceding his lay-'\noff, and no provision is made for\nmilitary service.\n\u201cA lot of veterans are find\ning themselves unable to col\nlect unemployment compensa\ntion simply because they had\nto go to military service.\u201d ex\nplained Mr. Smith. \"These\nmen are being penalised for\ncount rate for the fourth time\nsince November and ordered\na further reduction in' bank\nreserve requirements.\nThe Reserve Board\u2019s credit\neasing moves indicated its con\ncern that the current recession\n\u2014the worst since the end of\nWorld War II\u2014was still a seri\nous problem that required action\nin the area of monetary policy.\nUnemployment at Record High\nUnemployment meanwhile,\ncontinued at a postwar high with\nthe Labor Dept, reporting that\nthe number of persona drawing\nunemployment compensation for\nthe week ending Apr. 5 totaled\n3,314,307, the highest total in\nthe 19 years of the program. The\nfigure represented 8 percent of\nworkers covered by the program,\nanother high since records have\nbeen kept.\nA possible worsening of the\nunemployment picture, was\npredicted by a member of the\nBureau of Labor Statistics.\nRay Larsen, who told the Na\ntional Social Welfare Assem\nbly that unemployment in\nMay and June might top 5.2\nmillion because of 1.5 million\nto 2 million students who en\nter the labor force annually.\nIn 1957, he noted, unemploy\nment rose 600,000 during the\nlate spring.\nThe current recession, which\nstarted in August 1957, did not\naffect last year's profit picture\nvery much, according to a report\nfrom the Federal Trade and the\nSecurities Exchange Commis\nsions.\nThey found that manufactur\ning corporation reaped the sec\nond largest profits after taxes\non record in 1957 at $15.4 bil\nlion while sales showed a 12.8\npercent increase over 1956.\nThe Commerce Dept, reported\nthat dividends climbed for the\nfirst three months of 1958 de\nspite the recession with the $2.8\nbillion total topping the figure\nfor the same period in 1957 by\n$14 million.\naccepting their country\u2019s call\nto duty.\n\u201cMen who entered service be\nfore January 31, 1055 can re\nceive compensation under the\nFederal government\u2019s ruling.\nBut many workers who entered\nservice at the end of 1055 or the\nbeginning of 1056 have returned\nfrom their two-year hitch to\nfind\nthemselves\nin a\nlayoff\u201d\nstatus, or laid off from work ac\ncording to' seniority shortly af\nter their return to work\u2014and\nbefore they were able to ac\ncumulate 20 weeks of work.\n\"These men now are cut off\nfrom unemployment compensa\ntion, unjustly, we believe.\u201d\nThe. resolution suggests that\nthe BUC \u201cfreeze\u201d the worker\u2019s\nbase period during his military\nservice, so that when he returns\nto work, he can use the base\nperiod.\nEfforts should also be made\nto win compensation retroac\ntively for veterans who have\nalready lost their compensation\nunder the present rulings, the\nresolution says.\nYou Auto Buy Now\n1957\nCHEVROLET Bel Air 3\nDoor. Radio,\nHeater. Automatic\n$2195\n1957\nFORD Fleetline SOO, 3 Door.\nAutomatic\nRadio, Heater,\n$1895\n1956\nMERCURY Door. Hard\nTop. Radio,\nHeater, Mercomatic\n$1295\n1956\nFORD Victoria, 4 Door.\nRadio. Heater,\n2-tone, Fordomatic\n$1545\n1955\nWagon\nCHEVROLET 3 Door,\nStation\n$1195\n\nNO DOWN SKOALS\n$95.00 AND UP\n50 Plymouth 2 Door\n51 Chrysler Windsor Hardtop\n53 Ford C-8-2 Door\n55 Ford C-8-4-Door, ss\nLEE MOTORS\n911 Cherry St. CH 3-6225\nReconditioned and Guarantied\nPOWER\n\nMOWERS\n$2090\nCENTURY POWER MOWER\n4409 BENNETT near SPICER MFC.\nj,\nC\nV","height":"26872","width":"19636"}}
